{
  "texts": [
    "In sum, we find evidence that the patterns in emotion attribution follow gendered lines, answering RQ1.",
    "Next, we address the question of whether the differences described in the previous section are arbitrary, reflect actual differences in lived experiences, or are based on societal stereotypes about the emotional capabilities of the genders.",
    "We have seen that the models consistently show distinct gendered emotion associations (see Figure 2 and the aggregated frequencies in Table 5 in Appendix B).",
    "These associations are consistent with existing literature on emotional stereotypes (see Section 2):",
    "Women are commonly associated with SAD-NESS and JOY."
  ]
}